{"timestamp":"2026-05-05T15:26:51.661Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"call_NSyKBGkhzR84qzlGOgDobJlp","output":"Chunk ID: 341cc0\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 1399\nOutput:\n# Entire Skills Tutorial\n\nThis tutorial shows how to use Entire skills to explain code, investigate changes, search history, and hand work off between agents:\n\nBy the end, you will:\n\n1. understand what each skill does\n2. install the skills locally\n3. practice the exact prompts and commands to use\n4. build a tiny app so the skills have real code to work against\n\n## What Each Skill Is Good For\n\n| Skill | Best for | Example prompts | Why it helps |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- |\n| `session-handoff` | Switching agents, resuming later, summarizing recent work | `hand off this session`<br>`hand off the codex session`<br>`prepare a handoff for Claude Code` | Saves time, prevents duplicate work, preserves context |\n| `explain` | Understanding why a function, file, or change exists | `/explain src/main.ts`<br>`/explain parseConfig`<br>`Explain why auth.ts exists` | Great for onboarding, reveals intent, separates design decisions from accidental complexity |\n| `what-happened` | Investigating a specific block of code or recent change | `what happened here: src/app.ts:15-32`<br>`what happened at src/app.ts:21`<br>`tell me why this code is like this` | Useful in review, helps debug regressions, gives targeted provenance |\n| `search` | Finding prior work, earlier prompts, checkpoints, or similar implementations | `search past work for rate limiting`<br>`find checkpoints about auth`<br>`have we done this before?` | Helps reuse prior work, surfaces decisions, turns old history into something searchable |\n\n## Prerequisites\n\nBefore using these skills, make sure you have:\n\n1. Git installed\n2. an AI agent supported by Entire\n3. the `entire` CLI installed\n\n> Note:\n> This tutorial uses Codex for the examples because it is one of the simplest ways to try these skills from this repo.\n> If you use Claude Code, Gemini CLI, or another supported tool, the same skill concepts still apply.\n\n## Step 1: Install the Skills\n\nChoose the setup path that matches your tool:\n\n| Tool | Install |\n| --- | --- |\n| Codex | `mkdir -p ~/.agents/skills`<br>`cd ~/.agents/skills`<br>`git clone https://github.com/entireio/skills.git entire` |\n| Universal `skills` CLI | `npx skills add https://github.com/entireio/skills --all` |\n| Claude Code | `/plugin marketplace add entireio/skills`<br>`/plugin install entire` |\n| Gemini CLI | `gemini extensions install https://github.com/entireio/skills` |\n\n## Step 2: Install and Configure Entire CLI\n\nInstall Entire:\n\n```bash\nbrew tap entireio/tap\nbrew install --cask entire\n```\n\nOr, if you use Go:\n\n```bash\ngo install github.com/entireio/cli/cmd/entire@latest\n```\n\nConfirm it works:\n\n```bash\nentire version\n```\n\n## Step 3: Create a Project\n\nWe are going to build a tiny app called `bug-notes`.\n\nThis project is enough to:\n\n- generate history\n- make changes worth explaining\n- create checkpoints worth searching\n\nCreate the project:\n\n```bash\nmkdir bug-notes\ncd bug-notes\ngit init\nnpm create vite@latest . -- --template vanilla\nnpm install\ngit add .\ngit commit -m \"Initial Vite app\"\n```\n\nRun it:\n\n```bash\nnpm run dev\n```\n\n## Step 4: Enable Entire in the Project\n\nFrom inside `bug-notes`:\n\n```bash\nentire enable -y\nentire login\n```\n\nAt this point, your project is ready to record session context and checkpoints.\n\n## Step 5: Build the Mini App With Your Agent\n\nOpen the repo in your AI agent and give it a focused task.\n\nSuggested prompt:\n\n```text\nBuild a tiny bug tracker in this Vite app.\nRequirements:\n- Add a form with title and status\n- Save bugs in local state\n- Show a list of bug notes\n- Allow filtering by open and fixed\n- Keep the code simple and readable\n```\n\nOnce the agent finishes, commit the result:\n\n```bash\ngit add .\ngit commit -m \"Build bug notes app\"\n```\n\nThat commit is important because the skills become much more useful once there is committed history plus Entire checkpoint data.\n\n## Step 6: Make Several Distinct Changes So `search` Has Something Real To Find\n\nThe `search` skill is most valuable when there are multiple sessions with distinct concepts, not just one generic feature. Do these as separate chunks of work and commit after each one.\n\n### Change 1: persistence\n\nSuggested prompt:\n\n```text\nAdd localStorage persistence so bug notes survive refresh.\nAlso add a small empty state when no notes exist.\n```\n\nCommit:\n\n```bash\ngit add .\ngit commit -m \"Add persistence and empty state\"\n```\n\n### Change 2: duplicate detection\n\nSuggested prompt:\n\n```text\nAdd duplicate bug detection.\nIf a user tries to add a bug note with the same title as an existing one, show an inline validation message and prevent the duplicate.\n```\n\nCommit:\n\n```bash\ngit add .\ngit commit -m \"Prevent duplicate bug entries\"\n```\n\n### Change 3: severity badges\n\nSuggested prompt:\n\n```text\nAdd a severity field with values low, medium, and high.\nShow a colored severity badge in the bug list and allow filtering by severity.\n```\n\nCommit:\n\n```bash\ngit add .\ngit commit -m \"Add severity badges and filter\"\n```\n\nNow you have three distinct stories in history:\n\n- persistence\n- duplicate detection\n- severity filtering\n\nThat gives `search` much better material than a single vague feature.\n\n## Step 7: Practice Each Skill\n\n### Exercise A: `explain`\n\nAsk:\n\n```text\n/explain src/main.js\n```\n\nOr:\n\n```text\nExplain why the persistence logic exists\n```\n\nWhat you should notice:\n\n- the skill is trying to connect the code to the original session context\n- this is different from a normal code explanation, which only describes current behavior\n\n### Exercise B: `what-happened`\n\nFind a specific code range first:\n\n```bash\nnl -ba src/main.js | sed -n '1,220p'\n```\n\nThen ask:\n\n```text\n"}}
